value.value: The innermost of the four oocyte haploid nuclei after the second meiotic division following fertilization. The other 3 nuclei form the polar body nuclei. The female pronucleus migrates to the center of the embryo to fuse with the male pronucleus.

Haploid nucleus formed by the two meiotic divisions following oocyte ovulation. There are 3 polar body nuclei, located in a single file roughly perpendicular to the dorsal surface and to the long axis of the embryo. The fourth, and most inner of the haploid nuclei, forms the female pronucleus. The polar body nuclei are surrounded by yolk-free cytoplasm.

An organism that is undergoing embryogenesis (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). Embryogenesis begins with a fertilized egg, and finishes with hatching at the end of embryonic stage 17 (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997).

The outer region of cytoplasm of a syncytial blastoderm embryo. It has a distinct cytoskeletal structure, different from the rest of the cytoplasm, and encompasses the region to which nuclei migrate during blastoderm stages.

Embryo that is in the cleavage stage, which encompasses the first 13 rapid divisions after fertilization, corresponding to embryonic stages 1-4, prior to cellularization (Hartenstein, 1993; Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). The first seven divisions are synchronous (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). During the course of the subsequent three divisions, most of the nuclei approach the surface, to form the syncitial blastoderm (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). They then divide asynchronously a further three times, bringing the total number of cells to around 5000 (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997).
Nucleus found in the embryo during cleavage stage, including stages 1 to 4.
Yolk-free cytoplasmic region that surrounds each zygotic nucleus in the embryonic syncytium together with its nucleus starting from stage 1.

Nucleus that stays behind in the yolky interior of the syncytial embryo following the migration of a subset of nuclei to the periphery from cycle 8. There are around 50 of these nuclei. Yolk nuclei cease dividing in cycle 10 and become polyploid.
A portion of developing embryonic tissue defined by the simultaneous mitotic division of all of its component cells.

The first mitotic domain to complete interphase 14 and enter mitosis, doing so approximately 70 minutes after the start of interphase 14. It is located dorsolaterally at the anterior the animal, and is bilaterally symmetric.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Bilaterally symmetric mitotic domain that includes ventral cells immediately anterior to the cephalic fold and a contiguous stripe of cells that extends dorsally along the anterior face of the cephalic fold.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Unpaired mitotic domain that straddles the dorsal midline near the anterior tip of the embryo.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Bilaterally symmetric domain occupying the posterior tip of the germ band. Mitosis begins just when germ band elongation starts.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Large, bilaterally paired mitotic domain of the embryo lying on the dorsolateral surface immediately anterior to the cephalic furrow and on the contiguous anterior face of the cephalic furrow.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Bilaterally paired mitotic domain predominantly lying on the dorsolateral surface of the embryo, just posterior to the cephalic fold. The domain's anterior margin lies inside the cephalic fold, on its posterior face.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Bilaterally paired mitotic domain of the embryo located wholly within the cephalic fold.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Unpaired mitotic domain of the embryo located immediately ahead of the 'T' at the anterior end of the ventral furrow, straddling the ventral midline. Along with mitotic domain 9, this domain is distinguished by most of its cells dividing along axes perpendicular to the embryonic surface.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Large, bilaterally paired mitotic domain located anterior to the cephalic fold, adjacent and ventral to mitotic domain 5. Along with mitotic domain 8, this domain is distinguished by its cells dividing along axes perpendicular to the embryonic surface.
The largest of the mitotic domains. Between 55 and 65 minutes after mitosis 14 the cells of this domain invaginate to create the ventral furrow.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: A little after 80mins after mitosis 14, mitosis begins simultaneously in five dorsolateral sites on each side of the embryo.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Small bilaterally paired mitotic domain of the embryo, located immediately anterior to mitotic domain 4.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Bilaterally paired mitotic domain that, along with mitotic domain 22, forms a pouch-like invagination beneath the posterior tip of the elongating germ band which holds the pole cells. The cells of mitotic domain 13 form a ring around the opening of the pouch.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: In each half of the embryo, this mitotic domain consists of a row of one or two cells wide immediately lateral to the ventral furrow. The two rows of cells that form this domain lie on opposite sides of mitotic domain 10 in the blastoderm-stage embryo, but are brought together at the ventral midline when domain 10 invaginates.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: A mitotic domain region that is approximately 1 cell-wide and surrounds mitotic domains 8 and 23.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Unpaired, chalice-shaped mitotic domain that straddles the dorsal midline, between mitotic domains 1, 3 and 20.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Along the length of the germ band, this long narrow domain, one or two cells wide, separates mitotic domains A and 11.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Unpaired mitotic domain on the dorsal midline lying just posterior to mitotic domain 18, and between the paired members of domain B.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Bilaterally paired mitotic domain that, along with mitotic domain 13, forms a pouch-like invagination beneath the posterior tip of the elongating germ band which holds the pole cells.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Small, unpaired mitotic domain which, in the just-cellularized blastoderm, occupies the anterior tip of the embryo.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Small, late-dividing mitotic domain located in the presumptive head, between mitotic domains 2, 5, and 9. When the first domains are entering mitosis, mitotic domain 24 is located on the lip of the cephalic fold, but by the time the cells of this domain divide, the opening of the cephalic fold has repositioned mitotic domain 24 further forwards.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: At about 115mins after the onset of mitosis stage 14, the first cells in the ventral territory immediately adjacent to mitotic domain 14, divide. These first dividing cells constitute mitotic domain 25, whose metamerically reiterated members are located amongst the cells of domain M that begin division about 25mins later and will divide asynchronously.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: At blastoderm, prior to elongation, domain A is a wide band of cells straddling the dorsal midline and spanning the length of the germ band. Germ band elongation buckles and folds this domain. This domain becomes the amnioserosa.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Mitotic domain B is a paired domain that occupies a wedge-shaped area on the dorsolateral surface of the presumptive head.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Region surrounding the segmentally reiterated mitotic domain 25 cells. Cells of mitotic domain M do not divide with any obvious bilateral symmetry.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Mitotic domain N is the ventrolateral region surrounding mitotic domains 16, 17 and 21.

definition.value: See figure 1 of Foe (1989) for an atlas of mitotic domains.

value.value: Protuberance of the embryonic head that develops at stage 12. It forms from the dorsal part of the gnathal segments. It gives rise to the frontal sac.
Cytoplasmic bud that forms at the posterior pole of the embryo during cycle 9. Pole buds give rise to the pole cells.

Cell that forms at the posterior pole of the early embryo. It is a diploid germ cell that enters into close association with the somatic cells of the gonad and proliferates during larval stages to give rise to male or female germ cells.

definition.value: Can be identified by expression of vasa (Slaidina et al., 2020).

value.value: The middle underside of the embryo, where the midline neurons and midline glia develop (Kearney et al., 2004).

definition.value: Anlage in statu nascendi that will give rise to the clypeo-labral anlage.

value.value: A squamous epithelial tissue that derives from the dorsal-most region of the cellular blastoderm and that covers the dorsal side of the embryo following germ-band retraction, prior to dorsal closure.

Furrow of the embryo that forms at the beginning of stage 6, and extends to cover most of the length of the ventral midline (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1985). It forms mesoderm and endoderm (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1985). The lips fuse shortly after invagination, so that it is no longer visible as a furrow after stage 7 (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1985).

Furrow of the embryo that roughly separates the procephalon from the gnathal, thoracic and abdominal regions (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1985). It appears during stage 6, extending from the dorsal midline as an almost vertical slit, then progressively reclines posteriorly (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1985). It vanishes during stage 11, as its cells contribute to the gnathocephalon (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1985).

Furrow that extends over the dorsal part of the embryo, anterior to the posterior transverse furrow (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1985). It appears during stage 6 and deepens during stage 7 (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1985). It migrates anteriorly by cells moving in and out of the fold (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1985). It is no longer visible by stage 9 and its cells contribute to the amnioserosa (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1985).

Furrow that extends over the dorsal part of the embryo, posterior to the anterior transverse furrow (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1985). It appears during stage 6 and deepens during stage 7 (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1985). It migrates anteriorly by cells moving in and out of the fold (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1985). It is no longer visible by stage 9 and its cells contribute to the amnioserosa (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1985).

Furrow of the embryo that separates each segment into anterior and posterior compartments (Larsen et al., 2008). It forms in the ventrolateral region of its segment in early stage 11 and disappears late in stage 11 (Larsen et al., 2008).
Furrow that forms between segments during embryonic stage 11 and persists to the larval stage (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1985).

Embryonic collection of cells that will give rise to the ventral, metameric regions of the embryo (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). It comprises precursors of the gnathal, thoracic and abdominal segments (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997).
Contiguous region of early embryonic cells that will invaginate to form the mesoderm during gastrulation (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997).

Contiguous region of early embryonic cells of the ectoderm anlage that forms a single-cell border between the anlagen of the mesoderm and ventral ectoderm (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997; Stathopoulos and Newcomb, 2020). As the mesoderm invaginates and the ventral furrow closes, the two rows of cells come together to form the mesectoderm at the ventral midline of the embryo (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997).
